AGI -&nbsp; Israeli prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, told the ministers of his party, Likud, during a meeting that Israel will respond to the Iranian attack of the weekend, but he will have to do so wisely and not belly. The Israeli public broadcaster Kan.<br> Netanyahu, according to the broadcaster, said that Iran "must wait nervously without knowing when the attack could come, just as it has
forced to do the same to Israel."
&nbsp;
Kan also reports that Israel has committed to updating the United States before any attack so as to give time to American troops in the region to prepare for Iranian retaliation. The engagement came as a result of Washington's anger for the fact that Israel had not given a proper warning before hitting the Iranian consulate in Damascus, killing several generals of the Guardians of the Revolution and triggering the retaliation of the Islamic Republic.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The Chief of Staff of Idf, Herzi Halevi, in a statement from the Nevatim Air Base, said that "Iran wanted to damage the strategic capabilities of the State of Israel - this is something that had never happened before. We were prepared for the 'Iron Shield' operation - preparation that led Iran to meet even air superiority," said Halevi, as the Israeli media reports.
&nbsp;
"We think that the State of Israel is very strong and can face Iran alone, but with such a large and so far threat, we are always happy to have (the United States) with us," said Halevi. "We are looking forward, we are evaluating our steps, and the launch of so many missiles, cruise missiles and drones in the territory of the State of Israel will receive an answer," warned the Chief of Staff.
<h2>Teheran, more powerful response ready &nbsp;</h2>
Iran does not want an increase in tension in the Middle East region, but is ready for an immediate and more powerful attack than that carried out on the night of April 14, in the event of an Israeli attack, said Iranian Foreign Minister Hossein Amirabdollahian.<br> "Iran will respond with more powerful actions than before if Israel responds (at attacks)", said the second minister during his conversation with the British counterpart, reported by Iranian media. Moreover, the spokesman of the Iranian Foreign Ministry, Nasser Kanaani, stressed that Tehran does not seek to increase tensions in the region.
&nbsp;
"Iran has acted on the defence of its own security and national interests, as well as taking into account the inertia of the UN Security Council regarding Israel's use of force against the Iranian embassy in Damascus, as well as the irresponsible behaviour of the United States, Great Britain and France," he noted as the agency Tasnim reports.
<h2> The US: "How to react Israel decides"</h2>
If and how to react to the attack with drones and missiles from Iran is "decision that has to take Israel", the United States is not involved, said the spokesman of the US National Security Council John Kirby, in a briefing. To the question whether President Joe Biden urged Israel to show moderation after successfully dismissing Iran's attack, Kirby said that the president "exhorted the Prime Minister to think of what this would mean, for himself and for the rest of the region".
<h2>Tajani: "We work for de-escalation"</h2>
"We are working, like Italy, in the G7 to try to calm the water and avoid an enlargement of the conflict" in the Middle East. The Foreign Minister Antonio Tajani said this during the broadcast Fourth Power on Retequattro, where he emphasized that "the Italian government is working for peace, remaining the position of friendship towards Israel". "The G7, convened urgently by Prime Minister Meloni, yesterday launched a message of strong condemnation of Iran's attack. No one thinks of erasing Israel from the map," warned the head of the Farnesina.<br> "A message was also sent to Israel who won from the military point of view, should be satisfied with the military response," Tajani recalled, warning that "a military escalation would be very harmful to all".

